–Zesnulý","1052–Male":"1052–Zesnulý","1054–Male":"1054–Zesnulý","1060–Male":"1060–Zesnulý","1060–1106":"1060–1106","1082–1165":"1082–1165","1012–1077":"1012–1077","1014–Female":"1014–Zesnulá","about 1060":"okolo 1060","about 1082":"okolo 1082","1066":"1066","1077":"1077","1165":"1165","1054":"1054","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1052":"1052","1082":"1082","1060":"1060","1081":"1081","1106":"1106","1048":"1048","1014":"1014","1046":"1046","1012":"1012","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Francie","Beaminster, Dorset, England":"Beaminster, Dorset, Anglie","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Francie","Berwick, Dorset, England":"Berwick, Dorset, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1060–":"omkring 1060–Afdød","1048–Male":"1048–Afdød","1052–Male":"1052–Afdød","1054–Male":"1054–Afdød","1060–Male":"1060–Afdød","1060–1106":"1060–1106","1082–1165":"1082–1165","1012–1077":"1012–1077","1014–Female":"1014–Afdød","about 1060":"omkring 1060","about 1082":"omkring 1082","1066":"1066","1077":"1077","1165":"1165","1054":"1054","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1052":"1052","1082":"1082","1060":"1060","1081":"1081","1106":"1106","1048":"1048","1014":"1014","1046":"1046","1012":"1012","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Frankrig","Beaminster, Dorset, England":"Beaminster, Dorset, England","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Frankrig","Berwick, Dorset, England":"Berwick, Dorset, England"},"nl":{"about 1060–":"circa 1060–Overleden","1048–Male":"1048–Overleden","1052–Male":"1052–Overleden","1054–Male":"1054–Overleden","1060–Male":"1060–Overleden","1060–1106":"1060–1106","1082–1165":"1082–1165","1012–1077":"1012–1077","1014–Female":"1014–Overleden","about 1060":"circa 1060","about 1082":"circa 1082","1066":"1066","1077":"1077","1165":"1165","1054":"1054","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1052":"1052","1082":"1082","1060":"1060","1081":"1081","1106":"1106","1048":"1048","1014":"1014","1046":"1046","1012":"1012","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Frankrijk","Beaminster, Dorset, England":"Beaminster, Dorset, England","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Frankrijk","Berwick, Dorset, England":"Berwick, Dorset, England"},"en":{"about 1060–":"about 1060–Deceased","1048–Male":"1048–Deceased","1052–Male":"1052–Deceased","1054–Male":"1054–Deceased","1060–Male":"1060–Deceased","1060–1106":"1060–1106","1082–1165":"1082–1165","1012–1077":"1012–1077","1014–Female":"1014–Deceased","about 1060":"about 1060","about 1082":"about 1082","1066":"1066","1077":"1077","1165":"1165","1054":"1054","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1052":"1052","1082":"1082","1060":"1060","1081":"1081","1106":"1106","1048":"1048","1014":"1014","1046":"1046","1012":"1012","Normandie, France":"Normandy, France","Beaminster, Dorset, England":"Beaminster, Dorset, England","Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","Berwick, Dorset, England":"Berwick, Dorset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Russell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish: of Norman origin, from Old French and Anglo-Norman French <i>r(o)ussel</i>, a diminutive of Old French <i>rous(e)</i> ‘red, reddish’, used either as a nickname for someone with red hair or a ruddy complexion, or as a personal name. Compare   Rouse  . This Norman name has been established in Ireland since the 12th century. It has been reinforced in Britain and Ireland by Huguenot bearers of the name <i>Roussel</i>, of the same Old French origin.","English: habitational name from any of several places called Rushall (Norfolk, Staffordshire, Wiltshire) or possibly sometimes from Rusthall in Speldhurst (Kent). Rushall in Staffordshire derives from Old English <i>rysc</i> ‘rush, rushes’ + <i>halh</i> ‘nook, corner of land’. Rushall in Norfolk derives from an uncertain first element + Old English <i>halh</i>. Rushall in Wiltshire derives from an Old English personal name <i>Rust</i> (genitive <i>Rustes</i>) + <i>halh</i>. Rusthall in Speldhurst (Kent) probably derives from Old English <i>rust</i> ‘rust, rust color’ + <i>wella</i> ‘well, spring, stream’, but with a change in the final element due to influence from Middle English, Old English <i>hall</i> ‘hall, residence’, perhaps referring to a nearby building.","Americanized form of German <b>Rüssel</b>, from a pet form of any of various personal names formed with the element <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’."],"variants":[{"name":"Russler","meanings":["German (<b>Rüssler</b>):","occupational name for a farmer, from an agent derivative of <i>rüsseln</i> ‘to shallow plow’.","variant of <b>Rüssel</b> (see   Russell   2)."]},{"name":"Rouse","meanings":["English: nickname for a person with red hair or a ruddy complexion, from Middle English, Anglo-Norman French <i>rous(e)</i> ‘red(-haired)’ (from Latin <i>russ(e)us</i>).","Americanized form of German   Raus  .","Walloon and northern French (<b>Rousé</b>): variant of <b>Rosé</b> (see   Rose  )."]},{"name":"Russel","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Russell  .","German: from a pet form of <i>Russ</i>, see   Russ   2.","northwest German (<b>Rüssel</b>): probably a variant of   Rossel  ."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Informal short form of   Desmond ."],"variants":[{"name":"Desmond","meanings":["Transferred use of an Irish surname derived from the Gaelic byname <i>Deasmhumhnach</i> ‘(man from) south Munster’, an ancient Irish kingdom named after <i>Mumhu</i>, one of its early kings."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":6,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":26,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":36,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in th